problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in literature would. Evaluate $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60}$.
gpt_response:
To evaluate the expression $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60}$, we can simplify the expression by multiplying the numbers under the cube roots first. 

$12 = 2^2 \times 3$
$20 = 2^2 \times 5$
$15 = 3 \times 5$
$60 = 2^2 \times 3 \times 5$

Now, we can rewrite the expression as:
$\sqrt[3]{2^2 \times 3} \times \sqrt[3]{2^2 \times 5} \times \sqrt[3]{3 \times 5} \times \sqrt[3]{2^2 \times 3 \times 5}$

Multiplying the terms under the cube roots, we get:
$\sqrt[3]{12} \times \sqrt[3]{20} \times \sqrt[3]{15} \times \sqrt[3]{60}$ 
$= \sqrt[3]{2^2 \times 3} \times \sqrt[3]{2^2 \times 5} \times \sqrt[3]{3 \times 5} \times \sqrt[3]{2^2 \times 3 \times 5}$
$= \sqrt[3]{2^6 \times 3^2 \times 5^2}$
$= 2^2 \times 3 \times 5$
$= 60$

Therefore, $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60} = 60$.
